        "rating": 1,
        "relativeTimeDescription": "a month ago",
        "text": "I doubt staff will see this post and care much as there is a mix of positive and negative reviews, but the negative ones are not met with constructive criticism. This leads me to believe nothing will be done in my case which is fine. I hope this post can help others to make an educated decision.\n\nI can only judge based on my experience, but this company did a poor job of handling our situation. We have recently moved to Calgary from Ontario. Finding daycare for your child is difficult to say the least.\n\nWe were recommended to Zebra Crossing by someone who has used their services in the past. When we spoke with the mahogany center, they advised that registration was full and turnover was far and few between. They made it clear that we would need to be on a waitlist if we wanted any chance to have our two year old enrolled. The waitlist was also full and we were told, if something became available, they would let us know.\n\nWe were told we would have to pay a deposit and that would be applied to the first month registration fee. Unfortunately, when we moved to Calgary, we were forced to settle into a different community. We thought, okay we will get back our deposit and enroll our child in a different facility. We were providing good notice and as we were told the waitlist was full. The assumption was there were many others to take out place. The harm no loss.\n\nWhen we informed the staff at Zebra Crossing that we no longer required the waitlist, we would be moving on, they become defensive and said that we would need to talk to head office. This was my first clue something fishy was going on. Charlotte advised me someone from head office would call me back.\n\nThere was no call! There was a poorly put together email from Sameer Khakhi: manager of accounting finance & operations that read \"there was no deposit paid, only a signup/registration fee\". I was furious. I sent an email explaining, that I understand that we may have inconvenienced the business (which I don't understand if the capacity was full). I also, offered to give some of the $400 that was held hostage to them as good faith for their time. No one has even replied. $400 for a registration fee for a daycare your soon isn't attending? $400 to remain on the waitlist? And if you don't join, you lose the money? NO! This is cruel.\n\nBest of luck to anyone that goes here. Just wanted to make sure our family's voice was heard.\n\nRegards,\n\nChristopher Campbell",
